Ferritin channels throughout the small intestine","Hepcidin transporters in the jejunum","Transferrin receptors in the ileum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDietary iron absorption occurs primarily in the duodenum and proximal jejunum. Iron is absorbed via the divalent metal transporter 1 (\u003Cstrong\u003EDMT1) in the duodenum and proximal jejunum\u003C/strong\u003E following conversion from ferric (Fe3+) to ferrous (Fe2+) form by duodenal cytochrome B. This represents the main pathway for dietary iron uptake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepcidin\u003C/strong\u003E is a regulatory hormone that inhibits (not facilitates) iron absorption by causing degradation of ferroportin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeruloplasmin\u003C/strong\u003E is a copper-containing enzyme that oxidises iron for loading onto transferrin in plasma, but is not involved in its intestinal absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFerritin\u003C/strong\u003E is an intracellular iron storage protein and does not function as a channel for iron absorption in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransferrin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in cellular iron uptake from the bloodstream, not intestinal absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iron is absorbed in the duodenum and proximal jejunum via divalent metal transporter 1 (DMT1).","Ferritin is involved in the intracellular storage of iron."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Piskin E, Cianciosi D, Gulec S, Tomas M, Capanoglu E. Iron Absorption: Factors, Limitations, and Improvement Methods. ACS Omega. 2022;7(24):20441-20456. Published 2022 Jun 10. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35755397/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions",